ditor from May 2007 until August 2010 when he took up his current role. Mr Symonds is also a founding director of Reach-To-Teach, a charity that brings school education to tribal and migrant children in Gujarat. Mr Symonds is the author of “Softwar: and intimate portrait of Larry Ellison and Oracle” published in 2003. Prior to <em>The Economist</em> Mr Symonds was chief economics commentator of the Daily Telegraph (1981-86), Co-founder and Editorial Director of Newspaper Publishing plc (1986-94), Deputy Editor and the Executive Editor of the <em>Independent</em> (1986-94), business columnist for the <em>Sunday Express</em> (1995) and Director of Strategy for BBC Worldwide Television (1995-97).','Matthew Symonds','','publish','closed','closed','','matthew-symonds','','','2015-10-08 16:02:33','2015-10-08 15:02:33','',0,'http://dna.economist.in-beta8.co.uk/?post_type=people&#038;p=299',0,'people','',0),(300,1,'2015-09-30 15:36:49','2015-09-30 14:36:49','Matthew Symonds is Defence and Diplomatic Editor covering a wide range of security-related and foreign-policy issues including arms control and nuclear proliferation. He joined <em>The Economist</em> in 1997 as Technology and Communications Editor, later taking the roles of Political Editor and author of the \"Bagehot\" column, followed by Industry Editor from May 2007 until August 2010 when he took up his current role. Mr Symonds is also a founding director of Reach-To-Teach, a charity that brings school education to tribal and migrant children in Gujarat. Mr Symonds is the author of “Softwar: and intimate portrait of Larry Ellison and Oracle” published in 2003. Prior to <em>The Economist</em> Mr Symonds was chief economics commentator of the Daily Telegraph (1981-86), Co-founder and Editorial Director of Newspaper Publishing plc (1986-94), Deputy Editor and the Executive Editor of the <em>Independent</em> (1986-94), business columnist for the <em>Sunday Express</em> (1995) and Director of Strategy for BBC Worldwide Television (1995-97).','Matthew Symonds','','inherit','closed','closed','','299-revision-v1','','','2015-09-30 15:36:49','2015-09-30 14:36:49','',299,'http://dna.economist.in-beta8.co.uk/2015/09/30/299-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(301,1,'2015-09-30 15:38:32','2015-09-30 14:38:32','Henry Tricks is based in London as the Energy and Commodities Editor. He joined <em>The Economist</em> as capital-markets editor in January 2006, and became Finance Editor later that year. He was Tokyo Bureau Chief from August 2009 until April 2013, and bureau chief for Mexico and Central America from 2013 to 2015. Before joining <i>The Economist </i>he wrote for the <em>Financial Times</em> in London, was <em>FT </em>bureau chief in Mexico, and worked for Reuters in America, Mexico and Central America. For <i>The Economist</i> he has written special reports on the Pacific Rim, Japan, and global investment banking.','Henry Tricks','','publish','closed','closed','','henry-tricks','','','2015-10-08 17:56:09','2015-10-08 16:56:09','',0,'http://dna.economist.in-beta8.co.uk/?post_type=people&#038;p=301',0,'people','',0),(302,1,'2015-09-30 15:37:35','2015-09-30 14:37:35','','Henry Tricks','','inherit','closed','closed','','301-revision-v1','','','2015-09-30 15:37:35','2015-09-30 14:37:35','',301,'http://dna.economist.in-beta8.co.uk/2015/09/30/301-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(303,1,'2015-09-30 15:38:32','2015-09-30 14:38:32','<p>Henry Tricks joined <em>The Economist</em> as capital markets editor in January 2006, became Finance Editor in September 2006 and became Tokyo Bureau Chief in August 2009. Before that he wrote for the <em>Financial Times</em> in London, was <em>FT</em> bureau chief in Mexico, and worked for Reuters in America, Mexico and Central America. Henry has been interviewed on CNBC and the BBC World Service amongst others.</p>','Henry Tricks','','inherit','closed','closed','','301-revision-v1','','','2015-09-30 15:38:32','2015-09-30 14:38:32','',301,'http://dna.economist.in-beta8.co.uk/2015/09/30/301-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(304,1,'2015-09-30 15:39:50','2015-09-30 14:39:50','Vijay V. Vaitheeswaran is an award-winning senior correspondent for <em>The Economist</em>. He joined the editorial staff in 1992 as its London-based Latin America correspondent, and later opened the magazine\'s first bureau in Mexico City. From 1998 to 2006, he covered energy and the environment. From 2007 to 2011, his portfolio encompassed global health, pharmaceuticals and biotechnology. Vijay opened the newspaper’s first Shanghai bureau in 2012, and currently serves as the China Business Editor &amp; Shanghai Bureau Chief.\r\n\r\nHis latest book (published by Harper Collins) is “Need, Speed and Greed: How the New Rules of Innovation Can Transform Businesses, Propel Nations to Greatness, and Tame the World\'s Most Wicked Problems.” Kirkus Reviews declared it to be the “perfect primer to the post-industrial age.” He previously co-authored “ZOOM”, with Iain Carson, and “Power to the People”, two award-winning books about the future of cars and energy.\r\n\r\nVijay is a life member of the Council on Foreign Relations and an advisor on sustainability and innovation to the World Economic Forum. His commentaries have appeared in the <em>Wall Street Journal</em>, <em>Financial Times</em> and <em>New York Times</em>. He is a graduate of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.','Vijay Vaitheeswaran','','publish','closed','closed','','vijay-vaitheeswaran','','','2015-11-19 21:57:26','2015-11-19 21:57:26','',0,'http://dna.economist.in-beta8.co.uk/?post_type=people&#038;p=304',0,'people','',0),(305,1,'2015-09-30 15:39:50','2015-09-30 14:39:50','<p>Vijay V. Vaitheeswaran is an award-winning senior correspondent for <em>The Economist</em>. He joined the editorial staff in 1992 as its London-based Latin America correspondent, and later opened the magazine\'s first bureau in Mexico City. From 1998 to 2006, he covered energy and the environment. From 2007 to 2011, his portfolio encompassed global health, pharmaceuticals and biotechnology. Vijay opened the newspaper’s first Shanghai bureau in 2012, and currently serves as the China Business Editor &amp; Shanghai Bureau Chief. <br>&nbsp;<br>His latest book (published by Harper Collins) is “Need, Speed and Greed: How the New Rules of Innovation Can Transform Businesses, Propel Nations to Greatness, and Tame the World\'s Most Wicked Problems.” Kirkus Reviews declared it to be the “perfect primer to the post-industrial age.” He previously co-authored “ZOOM”, with Iain Carson, and “Power to the People”, two award-winning books about the future of cars and energy.<br>&nbsp;<br>Vijay is a life member of the Council on Foreign Relations and an advisor on sustainability and innovation to the World Economic Forum. His commentaries have appeared in the <em>Wall Street Journal</em>, <em>Financial Times</em> and <em>New York Times</em>. He is a graduate of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.</p>','Vijay Vaitheeswaran','','inherit','closed','closed','','304-revision-v1','','','2015-09-30 15:39:50','2015-09-30 14:39:50','',304,'http://dna.economist.in-beta8.co.uk/2015/09/30/304-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(306,1,'2015-09-30 15:44:02','2015-09-30 14:44:02','Matthew Valencia joined <em>The Economist</em> in 1995 as banking correspondent, and in 1998 moved to Frankfurt to cover German business and finance. He returned to London in 2000 to edit the newspaper\'s business pages. In 2003 he took over the running of Global Agenda, the daily news and analysis section of <em>The Economist</em> online. He covered US finance from New York from 2006 to 2012. His current beat is features, investigations and other special assignments.','Matthew Valencia','','publish','closed','closed','','matthew-valencia','','','2015-10-08 17:56:55','2015-10-08 16:56:55','',0,'http://dna.economist.in-beta8.co.uk/?post_type=people&#038;p=306',0,'people','',0),(307,1,'2015-09-30 15:44:02','2015-09-30 14:44:02','<