aw oversees social media innovation at <em>The Economist</em>. She currently leads a team of eight journalists focused on adapting and distributing its journalism across social media, chat apps and emerging platforms. Denise previously spent five years working as a journalist at the <em>Financial Times</em> in London and Hong Kong, where she helped to set up several news startups focused on emerging markets. A native of Toronto, Denise has lived and worked in London, Hong Kong, Shanghai and Utrecht.','Denise Law','','inherit','closed','closed','','90-revision-v1','','','2016-04-12 13:52:27','2016-04-12 12:52:27','',90,'http://mediadirectory.economist.com/2016/04/12/90-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(560,1,'2016-04-12 14:34:53','2016-04-12 13:34:53','Ananyo Bhattacharya is The Economist\'s Science correspondent. Before joining the Economist, he spent five years at Nature, first as the journal\'s Online News Editor then as Chief Online Editor. He has also worked for Chemistry World and Research Fortnight. He holds a PhD in protein crystallography.','Ananyo Bhattacharya','','inherit','closed','closed','','72-revision-v1','','','2016-04-12 14:34:53','2016-04-12 13:34:53','',72,'http://mediadirectory.economist.com/2016/04/12/72-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(561,1,'2016-04-12 17:33:50','2016-04-12 16:33:50','Slavea Chankova is a Data Journalist. She joined <em>The Economist</em> in March 2015 and wrote primarily about health-care policy for a year. Previously, she worked in international development, specialising in surveys and evaluations of health-care programmes.  She has appeared on BBC Radio 4.','Slavea Chankova','','publish','closed','closed','','slavea-chankova','','','2016-04-12 17:33:50','2016-04-12 16:33:50','',0,'http://mediadirectory.economist.com/?post_type=people&#038;p=561',0,'people','',0),(562,1,'2016-04-12 17:33:43','2016-04-12 16:33:43','','Slavea Chankova','','inherit','open','closed','','slavea-chankova','','','2016-04-12 17:33:43','2016-04-12 1