2/15/the-scottish-referendum-did-poverty-affect-voting/ \r\n\r\nThe Scottish Referendum: Did poverty affect voting?\r\nsharpescienceuk.wordpress.com\r\nThe 2014 Scottish Independence Referendum was undoubtedly one of the most discussed UK political events of the past decade. Numerous polls initially seemed to indicate a comfortable win for the ‘No...\r\n\r\n\r\nI was wondering if I could have a comment from you on my findings? Why do you think there was this relationship between child poverty and voting \'Yes\'? Any thoughts or opinions at all would be most appreciated, and I will of course send you the published article.\r\n\r\nThank you for your time,\r\n\r\nKatharine Sharpe'),(234,'Hello\r\nI am Journalist Abedalqader Hammad from Palestine - Gaza Strip\r\ni work reports, interviews and follow-ups daily in English and Arabic\r\nI\'m willing to work with you\r\n I have experience in the field of journalism for more than 15 years\r\nKnowing that I was working in the official Palestinian agency\r\n \"Wafa\" news and I was working in the writing of reports and stories in\r\n the newspaper Alaamarat today\'s English and irin newspaper, MEE (middleeasteye) and another newspapers \r\nthis some examples of my work has been previously published\r\nhttp://www.middleeasteye.net/in-depth/features/young-musicians-hone-their-skills-gaza-s-only-music-school-101944567\r\nhttp://www.irinnews.org/hov/72234/opt-maryam-al-muqayyed-60-the-wheel-of-life-has-completely-stopped\r\nhttp://www.irinnews.org/report/61971/opt-gaza-s-teetering-tower-of-debt\r\nhttp://www.irinnews.org/report/61838/opt-fishermen-suffer-naval-restrictions\r\nhttp://www.irinnews.org/report/61855/opt-palestinian-agricultural-losses-top-us-1-billion\r\nhttp://www.middleeasteye.net/in-depth/features/turkey-finances-largest-mass-wedding-ever-seen-gaza-77629592\r\nPlease reply'),(240,'Sarah Birke is The Economist‘s Middle East Bureau Chief based in Beirut; Prior to this role she was Middle East and North Africa Correspondent, reporting from Cairo on over 20 countries in the region. A specialist in Syria, she was based in Damascus for three years and Beirut in neighbouring Lebanon for a further two. Prior to joining The Economist, she wrote for a range of publications including the Wall Street Journal and The Times (London). She has also contributed to the New York Review of Books blog, London Review of Books blog and The New Republic. Sarah also lived in Italy for two years and spent time wandering Liberia in west Africa'),(248,'Dear Zanny Minton Beddoes\r\n\r\nLEAD (all you need to know if you are in a hurry): \r\n\r\nIn my eyes the Economist is the World\'s cognitively leading newspaper and you are one of the most interesting media leaders at this year\'s Davos Meeting. So logically as Swiss National Television\'s longtime Ten o\'Clock News anchor I would love to have you in our sixty minutes philosophical talkshow broadcasted to Switzerland, Germany and Austria. \r\n\r\nTEXT (all the details once you have 4 minutes of your precious time)\r\n\r\nIt would be a great opportunity to welcome you during the WEF in Davos on the 21 or 22 January in our TV-show Sternstunde Philosophie, hosted by Swiss National Television\'s longtime Ten o\'Clock News anchor (and WEF participant) Stephan Klapproth, broadcasted in Switzerland, Germany and Austria. I\'m aware you speak German perfectly and it would be possible to record the dialogue in German.\r\n\r\nSternstunde Philosophie is a sixty minutes weekly talk show on philosophical, scientific and political issues recorded without any commercial breaks. The program has gained an excellent reputation as a place of international dialogue focusing on essential questions. We are quite proud to have an audience in the German speaking world who dedicatedly watches and feedbacks our program. Among our guests were personalities such as the Dalai Lama, Kofi Annan, Joschka Fischer, Carla del Ponte, Peter Sloterdjik, Michail Chodorkowski, just to name a few.\r\n\r\nThe WEF would be a perfect chance to talk with you about the economic situation of different parts of the world.  But I would like to talk with you also about your job as editor in chief with the Economist and questions like \"Can we understand the world we live in?” \r\n\r\nOf course we are able to pay a fee of 1000 CHF.\r\n\r\nIt would be a great honour for us to have you as our guest. Looking forward to hearing from you, we remain\r\nyours sincerely,\r\n\r\nStephan Klapproth\r\n\r\nAnchor News & Philosophy \r\n\r\nSwiss National Television'),(256,'Hi there, would Andreas be available tonight at 11.05pm to speak to BBC national news network Radio 5 Live about the latest discussions in Brussels over the UK relationship with the EU?\r\nIt would be great to get Andreas\' insight and reflect the German perspective on our programme tonight.\r\nPlease email or call me. If Andreas is not available perhaps there is someone else who could help instead?\r\nThank you,\r\nLaura'),(264,'Hi there, would Andreas be available tonight at 11.05pm to speak to BBC national news network Radio 5 Live about the latest discussions in Brussels over the UK relationship with the EU?\r\nIt would be great to get Andreas\' insight and reflect the German perspective on our programme tonight.\r\nPlease email or call me. If Andreas is not available perhaps there is someone else who could help instead?\r\nThank you,\r\nLaura'),(279,'Dear Ms Rocco,\r\n\r\nHope my message finds you fine.\r\n\r\nI would like to submit the following post for your review: http://farashak.tumblr.com/post/135479594827/art-basel-2015-on-the-stabbing\r\n\r\nKindest Regards,\r\n\r\nM. Kouvatsou'),(286,'Dear Mr. Coggan,\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMy name is Peter Bass and I am making a documentary about my home town of Farnborough, Hampshire entitled \'i.am.peter\'.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nI am using my hometown as a microcosm to comment on universal political matters.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nI would be really interested in interviewing you to get your perspective and experience of politics in the UK and in general.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMy aim is to explore issues that affect everyone and principally to engage with the unengaged and to inspire them to get more involved in their community.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nI can come to London for this on any Wednesday in the new year at your convenience. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPlease if you could let me know if you would be able to do this and when you might be free to do so.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nYour input would be of real value to the documentary and I\'d be very grateful for your support. Thank you.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nKind regards,\r\n\r\nPeter Bass\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\niampeterfilm@gmail.com'),(294,'Ever wondered how big Santa’s sleigh would need to be to carry a gift for every child across the globe (number of TEUs)? How about how much milk and cookies Santa ingests during his Christmas run? The answer to both these questions is in an infographic we\'ve prepared and would be pleased to share.'),(302,'Hi Henry,\r\n\r\nI am a Fulbright scholar in the public policy school of Oregon State University. I previously served as an advisor to the minister of economy and the energy commission in Afghanistan. I wrote an article on TAPI gas pipeline which connects Central Asia to South Asia via Afghanistan. The pipeline is a pressing issue in the media, especially when the heads of four partner countries inaugurated the project through a groundbreaking ceremony in Turkmenistan on December 13th, 2015. \r\nI would like the article to be published in The Economist.\r\nYou may also read one of my previous analysis papers which got published in a policy think tank in Kabul.\r\nHere is a link: https://www.afghanistan-analysts.org/power-to-the-people-how-to-extend-afghans-access-to-electricity/\r\n\r\nPlease reply to this message to send you the full version of my article for your review.\r\n\r\nThanks,\r\nMohsin'),(310,'Hi James,\r\n\r\nI am a Fulbright scholar in the public policy school of Oregon 