a string of anti-terrorist raids and arrests across France’s urban banlieues that were often greeted with hostility rather than helping hands from the local population. In striking images caught by news cameras just days after the event, I can still hear and see the jeers from local youths as police left a Parisian banlieue empty handed after searching in vain for terrorist suspects. Like Molenbeek, France’s banlieues often contain large Muslim and immigrant-origin populations. Gilles Kepel, a globally respected French terrorism expert, is the author of Les banlieues de l\'Islam. Kepel has identified the tendency these peripheral urban areas have to emanate anti-state elements. It wasn’t meant to be like this.\r\n\r\nIn the mid 19th century Georges-Eugène Haussmann (in)famously transformed Paris to give the aesthetic look we now associate with it today. Haussmann rebuilt the city for numerous reasons; high amongst them were questions of state security. France had seen a multitude of violent uprisings in the poor working class areas of central Paris before this rebuilding project. Haussmann decided to bulldoze these areas and relocate the city’s poor to the outskirts of town. Here, theoretically, this ‘insurrectionary demographic’ would pose less of a threat and prove easier to surveil. Haussmannisation was copied in other Francophone cities, including Belgium where the planner responsible for Molenbeek, Jules Anspach, was dubbed the ‘Haussmann of Brussels’. Haussmann’s peripheral areas have become today’s banlieues, and the working class of Haussmann’s day have conflated with the immigrant class of the post-colonial era, a demographic simultaneously culturally, socially (and spatially) stigmatised.\r\n\r\nFrom widespread riots across French banlieues in 2005 to today’s terrorism, this urban topography appears to have proved problematic rather than conducive to state-security despite the pretentions of its design. The origins of this urban form become more problematic, and indeed controversial, when one considers that Haussmann’s main influence was the polemical figure Thomas Bugeaud. Bugeaud was, even by the standards of his day, a racist military figure responsible for France’s military conquest of Algeria in the 19th century. He was also responsible for the renovation of Algeria’s capital city, Algiers. As later imitated by Haussmann, Bugeaud practiced what was called ‘urban apartheid’ whereby the indigenous population was pushed to the outskirts of the city to the supposed benefit of the Europeans. But guess what? This form of military strategy in built space did not work.\r\n\r\nFrance lost a brutal war in Algeria in the mid 20th century in which Algiers played host to one of the world’s first modern terrorist campaigns. French security forces were only able to quell this terrorism with recourse to the highly controversial use of torture that allowed them to penetrate the urban support networks of their adversaries. However, the use of torture ultimately delegitimised the French cause and she consequently lost the war even if she had won a battle or two. This provides food for thought in the context of today’s ‘war on terrorism’. Le Figaro dubbed Salah Abdelsalem’s arrest last week a victory in the fight against terrorism. However, this was shortly followed by Monday’s horrific attacks in Brussels.  Abdelsalem was clearly but a small cog in a terrorist machinery that continued to turn in Molenbeek and elsewhere despite his capture.\r\n\r\nIt seems that a failed Francophone colonial-era strategy of urban apartheid continues to provide Islamist terrorists with relatively safe havens in which to materialise. So long as this continues, security services in Belgium, France and elsewhere may continue to win battles, but fail to win the war.'),(1629,'A person essentially assist to make critically posts I might state. That is the first time I frequented your web page and so far? I surprised with the research you made to make this 