icals released from the steel plants run by Formosa conglomerate contaminates the coastline causing massive fish deaths along the country’s central coast in recent days. Divers and people living along the coast have been admitted to the hospital and diagnosed with copper poisoning. Days later, hundreds of workers at a factory in Ho Chi Minh City were admitted to the hospital after their fish-lunch. The local authorities have been slow to act and the company that controls the plant had the audacity to say, \"[Vietnam] needs to choose whether to catch fish and shrimp or to build a state-of-the-art steel mill\". The issue has gotten way more complicated than anyone would have expected on the first day. At the first press conference held by the Ministry of Environment, the Minister denied that the associations of any factories with the disaster. \"It is between human activity or natural disaster. Right now there is no association between Formosa or any factories with the dead fishes along the coast\" he said. When a journalist raised the question of the copper poisoning, the Minister harassed on her and asked the entire crew to shut down the live interview. He said: \"Your question would harm out country\". \r\nAs I grew up in Quang Ngai Province, a coastal province in central Vietnam, the ocean was everything to me. It was where I went after school and somehow as a 10-year-old I thought I could help the fisherman with his job. It was where my best friend\'s mother has her little outdoor restaurant. It was where my father walked me along the coast and talked to me about my school day. All of that is lost. But it hurts us so much more to know that our government has made their decision to damage the environment. Today, that decision has caused one of the worst natural disasters in Vietnam\'s history. Today, that decision has made more than 23 thousands Vietnamese people who live on the fishing and ocean businesses lose their jobs. Today, that decision has threatened our 