ribed Cameron’s attitude as deeply disappointing and said that “thousands of children are sleeping rough in Europe tonight, vulnerable to exploitation and abuse and Britain should not be turning its back.”\r\n\r\nEmbed video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ORY1bIB1xCs\r\n\r\nHide and seek\r\n\r\nAccording to UNHCR, 35% of migrants entering the EU since January 2016 are children. Alone and vulnerable, they have fled their homes, seeking protection from war, violence and persecution. But since arriving in Europe, more than 10,000 of them have gone missing. The exact scale of the crisis is unclear, with numbers thought to be an underestimate due to lack of central data collection. \r\n\r\n“We know that thousands and thousands of children are simply unaccounted for, and the most horrifying thing of all is that we just have no idea where they are or what’s happening to them, and it’s that complete absence of information that should terrify us the most,” says Lily Caprani, Deputy Executive Director of Unicef UK.\r\n\r\nNext week, the Immigration Bill returns to the House of Commons, calling on the government to reconsider its position and offer sanctuary to these vulnerable children. A revised amendment will be reviewed; tabled by Lord Dubs, who himself arrived in Britain as a child-refugee after fleeing the Nazis in the 1930’s.\r\n\r\nThe new proposal removes the reference to 3,000 children and simply states that the government should make arrangements to relocate a “specified number of unaccompanied refugee children from other countries in Europe”. Whether this number will be determined by local authorities, a moral quota or some other ambiguous factor is yet to be specified.\r\n\r\nSo here we are, at a crossroad. With children as young as eight making adult decisions between life and death while their fate is decided amid the childish bickering of British politicians. As this crisis continues to grow out of hand, these children simply seek a safe place to grow up. They have made perilous journeys to Europe in search of refuge; now to find themselves being pushed away. \r\n\r\nPlayground politics. They can’t sit with us.\r\n\r\nIf they could go back to their countries, they would. But that’s the thing about war; it’s not very welcoming. These lost children have already lost too much. The joys of skipping to school, now replaced by skipping onto the back of lorries - not knowing whether or not they will make it. Not knowing what lies ahead. These children literally have nowhere to go. We simply cannot turn our backs.\r\n\r\nLiberal Democrat Leader Tim Farron believes “The vote on Monday is a test of Britain’s humanity. MPs must stand up for the values and traditions that make Britain great.” The safety and protection of refugee children needs to be at the heart of next week’s vote. \r\n\r\nLet us not become the monsters we warn our own children about. \r\n\r\nBy Thaslima Begum'),(2544,'Really, your book unexpectedly grabbed me. \r\nCover-to-Cover I traveled out of New Mexico and found a less traveled land, as far Western Thought goes. Yes, There has been a lot of ethnic killing here, too. But your insights on Putin parallel mine, also.'),(2551,'Dear Mr Piotrowski,  \r\n\r\nI\'m a brazilian freelance writer and I would like to offer a paid article about ex-president Lula da Silva to The Economist. To whom should I send it? \r\n\r\nThanks,\r\nGuilherme Hobbs.'),(2566,'Dear Mr. Wallace,\r\n\r\nI would like to send you an article for consideration of publication on The Economist\'s website. The piece sheds new light on the upcoming British referendum. Based on Hirschman\'s classic \"Exit, Voice Loyalty,\" I make the case that Brexit becomes a question of within or without influence. \r\n\r\nHere\'s the first paragraph:\r\n\r\nHeadlines these days feel like a perennial cacophony of \"Brexit will cause economic disaster\" versus \"Brexit fears wildly exaggerated.\" We\'re confronted with a stream of contradictory statistical projections