nI would be grateful if you could send me an email so that I can pass on the relevant information. \r\n\r\nI look forward to hearing from you. \r\n\r\nKind regards,\r\n\r\nScott'),(2808,'Hi Oliver I was involved with the article you did on clouds many years ago.....I am still at it but have made a number of advances recently which have not yet hit the public media..other than the West Wales Gazette!\r\n\r\n2 Things..how about considering\r\n\r\nAn article on this area \r\nand or\r\nAttend/speak a conference I am hosting in Wales in October\r\n\r\nCheers\r\n Bruce Moffett'),(2816,'Dear Mr. Carr,\r\n\r\nI would like to bring to your attention over-fishing in the Mediterranean. Constant over-fishing has led to 93% of fish stocks in the Mediterranean being over-exploited. \r\nRight now Med countries at the General Fisheries Commission for the Mediterranean (part of the UN\'s FAO organisation), are meeting in Malta to discuss this issue. \r\n\r\nOceana - an international organization focused solely on oceans, dedicated to achieving measurable change by conducting specific, science-based campaigns with fixed deadlines and articulated goals - is close to scuring a campaign victory to close aras of the Strait of Sicily from fishing to protect stocks. This would be a first for that area.\r\n\r\nhttp://eu.oceana.org/en/press-center/press-releases/oceana-unveils-images-fish-nursery-areas-damaged-bottom-trawling-strai-0 \r\n\r\nWe are also pushing for better regulation and transparency on EU vessels operating in non-EU waters, ahead of the EU fisheries ministers\' meeting in June. \r\n\r\nhttp://eu.oceana.org/en/press-center/press-releases/22000-eu-vessels-fishing-outside-eu-waters-highlights-need-greater \r\n\r\nIf you would like to know more about these topics, please do not hestitate to get in touch with me.\r\n\r\nWith kind regards, \r\nCRAIG LAWSON'),(2824,'Je suis rédacteur du journal ci-dessus et par ailleurs débatteur et un très vieil abonné à votre  hebdomadaire, . \r\nJe voudrais communiquer par correction à Madame Pedder un article que j\'ai écrit sur votre journal assorti de quelques considérations verbales globalement positives\r\n\r\n Yves Montenay'),(2832,'Dear Geoffrey Carr,\r\n\r\nSpecialized storytellers cast open the doors to scientific literacy. These narrators interpret jargon and explain the significance of research. Academic programs teach this craft, called science communication. One such program has chosen a new director [to be announced toward the end of June], as fledgling science communicators grapple with an economic shift, globalization, data journalism and new media.  \r\n\r\nIn the face of these challenges, skilled science communicators contribute to a publication’s profitability. Indeed, the most-read story of The Economist during 2015—a science story—beat out, among others, articles about the growing American aristocracy, gender inequality in education and internet pornography. The winning piece reported analysis of the DNA of the coywolf, a mixed breed of coyotes, wolves and dogs. \r\n\r\nBeginning January 1, 2017, [Name to be announced toward the end of June, 2016] of [current employment] in [geographic location] will direct the 35-year-old science communication program at the University of California, in the secluded redwood forest of Santa Cruz. Alumni of the ten-student-per-year program contribute to the prominence of science journals such as Nature (London and Washington, D.C.) and Science (Washington, D.C.). \r\n\r\nI propose to write a 1200-word piece about the future of science communication, anchored to the announcement of a new director for the UC Santa Cruz science communication program. The head of the selection committee as well as the current director have assured me time to interview the director (and themselves) before the name is announced. Due to this time-sensitivity, I would appreciate receiving your decision this week, if possible. \r\n\r\nThe UCSC program requires a science degree with six months of research. This background prepares reporters who now evaluate research for The Wall Street (New York) Journal, The New York Times and The Washington (District of Columbia) Post. Other graduates of the program freelance for the BBC (London), produce videos for NASA (Greenbelt, Maryland), investigate stories for BuzzFeed (New York City) and blog for National Geographic (Washington, D.C.). The new director would provide insight about how science communication programs prepare students for the challenges that these institutions face today . \r\n\r\nIn addition, I would interview other science communicators about the economic shift from print to online media. I would ask how globalization of news demands diversity in classrooms and newsrooms. I would explore how data journalism and new media affect reporting and editing.  \r\n\r\nI would interview science communicators such as Erika Check Hayden, reporter for Nature (San Francisco), for whom I have wrangled interviews; Marla Cone, senior editor at National Geographic, for whom I have written; Laura Helmuth, of The Washington Post\'s National’s health, science and environment team and fellow graduate of the program; and BuzzFeed\'s Peter Aldhous, a data journalist and instructor in the UCSC program.\r\n\r\nAmong other publications, I have written science news stories for the Stanford Woods Institute for the Environment, see \r\nhttps://woods.stanford.edu/news-events/news/global-climate-talks-timeline\r\n\r\nScience, see \r\nhttps://www.sciencemag.org/news/2015/06/what-will-pope-s-climate-encyclical-expected-18-june-say\r\n\r\nand Eos, see \r\nhttps://eos.org/articles/underground-water-reserves-found-hawaiis-high-country\r\n\r\nFor artwork, I suggest this image created by a student of the UCSC companion art illustration program, at California State University, Monterey Bay, see\r\nhttp://scicom.ucsc.edu/about/contact.html\r\n\r\nI disclose that as a graduate of the UCSC science communication program, I worked with other alumni to contribute an assessment of finalists for the director position. We have no position in deciding the final outcome. \r\n\r\nBest regards,\r\nLeslie Willoughby\r\n\r\nScience Journalist\r\nBoulder Creek, CA 95006 U.S.A.'),(2840,'Dear Mr. Cross,\r\n\r\nI would like to bring to your attention over-fishing in the Mediterranean. Constant over-fishing has led to 93% of fish stocks in the Mediterranean being over-exploited. \r\n\r\nThanks to a proposal tabled by Oceana, Mediterranean countries have agreed to close areas of the Strait of Italy to bottom fish trawling to rebuild fish stocks (juvenile fish stocks). This is a first for the General Fisheries Commission of the Mediterranean (under the umbrella of the UN\'s FAO). \r\n\r\nOceana - an international organization focused solely on oceans, dedicated to achieving measurable change by conducting specific, science-based campaigns with fixed deadlines and articulated goals.\r\n\r\nOur press releasees can be found here: http://eu.oceana.org/en/press-center/press-releases.\r\n\r\nIf you would like to know more about this topic, please do not hestitate to get in touch with me.\r\n \r\nWith kind regards, \r\nCraig Lawson\r\nOCEANA EUROPE'),(2854,'We\'re looking to potentially interview Ananyo for a new Channel 4 Programme \'What Britain Earns\'. The main subject we\'d be looking to cover would be how advancement in technology can decrease salaries (e.g. Uber driving down the cost of a taxi and therefore profit margins)'),(2862,'I am the owner of Insightview.eu - a Danish research company providing political and economic analysis to financial institutions. In this context, I go to China a few times every year. Therefore, I would like to meet Simon Rabinovitch, who met a few of my former colleagues from Scandinavia in April (SEB), if he has time. \r\n\r\nSee also http://www.insightview.eu/index.php?mid=12'),(2870,'Dear Ms Wroe,\r\nin August this year ADAC travel magazine will publish an edition on Southern England. We would be delighted if you´d agree on a short telephone interview on your work for the Economist. I will be more than happy to send you some samples of previous interviews.\r\nKind regards,\r\nHelmuth Meyer'),(2878,'I am a staff writer of JIJI PRESS and at the present, a fellow of Reuters institute for the study of journalism at University of Oxford. I am doing my research project about \'Reporting risk – a comparison between the coverage by British and German media of the Fukushima nuclear disaster’. In this project, I am planning to interview to scientific journalists and academian. I was wondering if you could cooperate with it.  I have been in Oxford and I can visit you whenever you want.'),(2886,'I am a staff writer of JIJI PRESS and a Journalist fellow of Reuters institute for the study of Journalism at University of Oxford. I have been researching about my essay \'Reporting risk – a comparison between the coverage by British and German media of the Fukushima nuclear disaster’.\r\nThen I am planning to interview to scientific journalists and academian in Britain and Germany. So I will be so glad if I could interview　you in London. I hope you could accept it. Thank you.'),(2902,'Sujet principal\r\nhttps://yvesmontenay.fr/2016/05/21/the-economist-encore-un-effort-pour-couvrir-le-monde/\r\n\r\n J\'ajoute qu\'à titre personnel, je suis un très ancien abonné, et ai fait votre  promotion dans des milieux où vous étiez mal connu, notamment chez les enseignants de l\'histoire et la géographie\r\n\r\nJ\'ai consulté votre Customer Service Centre,  mais n\'ai pas trouvé de rubrique adéquate'),(2910,'Dear Daniel Knowles,\r\n\r\nI wish to submit subject article to you for a possible publication on The Economist. In this article, I try to bring to the readers the role cinemas played in reshaping the Nigerian cinemas and cultures. It tells a story of the power of Hollywood especially in the way Anglophone West Africa tells its story through the cinemas. I capture this in a less academic but important ways.\r\n\r\nI believe with your professional editorial touch, we can make a big article out of this. It is compelling and illuminating.\r\n\r\nPlease kindly let me know if you would like to look at it.\r\n\r\nRegards,\r\nNuhu Othman   \r\nNigeria\r\n+234 803 646 3000 '),(2918,'Dear Ms Wroe,\r\n\r\nin August this year ADAC travel magazine will publish an edition on Southern England. We would be delighted if you´d agree on a short telephone interview on your work for the Economist. I will be more than happy to send you some samples of previous interviews.\r\n\r\nKind regards,\r\nHelmuth Meyer'),(2926,'Dear Sir or Madam, \r\n\r\nI hope this email finds you well.\r\n\r\nI do understand that you are very busy but I would like to present you an ice cream like you have never seen before in London. \r\n\r\nWe are the first and only food business that introduced the latest food trend to London: \"Rolled Ice Cream\" - an ice cream made in front of the customer with fresh ingredients and a theatrical ice cream making process. Fresh off the plate.  \r\n\r\nWould it be possible to arrange a brief phone call to discuss it in more detail. Please contact us via phone over +4407562828003\r\n\r\nPlease find below also our Facebook page and our website. \r\n\r\nFacebook.com/snobbywhale\r\n\r\nRolledicecream.net\r\n\r\nWe would be happy to hear from you. \r\n\r\nThanks in advance. \r\n\r\nAll the best, \r\n\r\nFranz, Florian & Patrick'),(2948,'Dear Economist,\r\n\r\nI am writing to you because I am hoping to film and document your work leading up to the Brexit referendum.\r\n\r\nI am a Danish journalist currently doing a series of documentaries on news around the World for the Nordic public service broadcasters. The series will be called Inside the News and we have just been to Iran and to Sweden to do documentaries about the working conditions of journalists there, and we are going to London next week to do a program on the press coverage of the build up to the Brexit referendum. \r\n\r\nIn this regard we are hoping to do an interview with your editor on the editorial choices of your newspaper and how you have chosen to cover the referendum.\r\n\r\nDo you think you would have the time for such an interview some time next week?\r\n\r\nBest wishes,\r\n\r\nTor'),(2956,'We’re organizing a segment tomorrow morning (Thursday, June 16)  from 9 to 10 am PDT for KQED’s Forum on the upcoming Brexit vote. Is there any chance that Emma or another correspondent for The Economist might be available for some or part of that hour for a phone interview on this? Our host is Michael Krasny. Thank you so much for letting us know as soon as you can.\r\n\r\nAll best,\r\nJulia Flynn Siler\r\nOn-call producer\r\nKQED Forum\r\n415-553-2262 o.\r\n415-269-2218 m.\r\n2601 Mariposa Street\r\nSan Francisco CA 94110-1426'),(2971,'Hello, \r\n\r\nI was wondering if I could please have the email for Natasha Loder. I would like to send a release from the Council of Accountable Physician Practices regarding a 2016 Nielsen healthcare survey that discusses the gaps in how patients are experiencing accountable care. \r\n\r\nThank you'),(2979,'Hello, this request is for David Rennie.\r\n\r\nI’m producing our popular show “Slate’s Political Gabfest” tomorrow, hosted by David Plotz, Jamelle Bouie, John Dickerson, host of Face The Nation on CBS.\r\n\r\nWe are seeking a guest to discuss the Brexit vote, and given Mr. David Rennie\'s location in Washington, his reporting expertise and media experience, I thought he would be a perfect person to ask. \r\n\r\nWe record tomorrow (15 Jun 2016) from 9-10:30 EST. We’re located at 1707 L St NW Suite 800 Washington DC. We can also link via phone or Skype.\r\n\r\nMany thanks for considering this on such short notice. If Mr. Rennie is not available, we would appreciate any other suggestions.\r\n\r\nSincerely,\r\nDaniel Bloom'),(2987,'I cover EU affairs for RTBF radio. I will be in London next week to cover the referendum. In this context, I would have like to get a brief interview with Anton La Guardia (if possible in French since it is for the radio) as an observer of the British media and the role it plays in the coverage of EU affairs.\r\nWill be available on Tuesday afternoon and Wednesday morning. The interview will not last more the 10 minutes'),(2995,'We are conducting a study at the request of two members of congress from the House Committee on Foreign Affairs.  We would really appreciate a brief interview withTom Wainright on issues related to the Bank Secrecy Act, US and OECD cooperative activities to combat money laundering to get his perspective on what areas should be included in our study.'),(3003,'Greetings, \r\n\r\nScottie Meyers here with Wisconsin Public Radio. I\'m writing on behalf of our midday program, “The Kathleen Dunn Show.” \r\n\r\nI\'m wondering if David Rennie is able to join us as a guest for an upcoming program.  We\'re looking to discuss the Brexit -- what it is, what are the possible implications and why America should be paying attention to it. Heard him yesterday on Slate’s “Political Gabfest” and he’s just terrific. \r\n\r\nI\'m hoping to set this up as a live interview on Wednesday, June 22nd from about 3:00-4:00 p.m. Eastern. It would be live Q&A with our host, Kathleen Dunn, and calls from listeners. There are breaks in there, but we could need you for the full hour. We could have him join by landline phone or arrange a studio. \r\n \r\nSome more about us: “The Kathleen Dunn Show” airs Monday through Thursday on Wisconsin Public Radio, which is the oldest and second largest public radio network in the country, with listeners across the nation. Our program is an hour long, live listener call-in show. It’s similar to WBUR’s “On Point.” \r\n\r\nPlease let me know if we can set this up. \r\n\r\nThanks so much. \r\n\r\nBest,\r\nScottie'),(3019,'I decided to leave a message here on your Bill Ridgers - Economist page instead of calling you. Do you need more likes for your Facebook Fan Page? The more people that LIKE your website and fanpage on Facebook, the more credibility you will have with new visitors. It works the same for Twitter, Instagram and Youtube. When people visit your page and see that you have a lot of followers, they now want to follow you too. They too want to know what all the hype is and why all those people are following you. Get some free likes, followers, and views just for trying this service I found: http://sirrico.net/yourls/p7gq'),(3027,'We\'d like to request a short phone/email interview for a correspondent who wrote an article called \"Master, Mistress or Mouse?\", which is about the UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon, published in May.\r\n\r\nPlease let me know the way to contact the correspondent who wrote the article.\r\n \r\nThank you in advance.'),(3035,'Dear Ms Pedder,\r\n\r\nI’m working for BERLIN POLICY JOURNAL, a new(ish) foreign affairs magazine published by the German Council on Foreign Relations.\r\n\r\nWe are presently looking for someone who could profile the (still undeclared) presidential candidate Emmanuel Macron, for our \"Close Up“ series:\r\n\r\nhttp://berlinpolicyjournal.com/tag/close-up/\r\n\r\nWould you be interested? \r\n\r\nWe are looking for a piece of approximately 2,000 words (or fewer), deadline would be next Monday or Tuesday.\r\n\r\nWe’d be honoured to have you on board!\r\n\r\nBest wishes,\r\nHenning Hoff\r\n\r\n--\r\nDr Henning Hoff\r\nEditor-at-Large\r\nINTERNATIONALE POLITIK\r\nExecutive Editor\r\nBERLIN POLICY JOURNAL\r\n\r\nGerman Council on Foreign Relations /\r\nDeutsche Gesellschaft für Auswärtige Politik (DGAP) e.V.\r\nRauchstrasse 17/18\r\n10787 Berlin\r\nGERMANY\r\n\r\n+49 (0)30 25 42 31-42\r\n+49 (0)174 7087 885 (cell)\r\n+49 (0)30 25 42 31-67 (fax)\r\nhoff@dgap.org\r\n\r\nwww.internationalepolitik.de\r\nwww.berlinpolicyjournal.com'),(3043,'Hi John, \r\n\r\nmy name is Laura Kneer, and I am a producer at Newstalk ZB -  New Zealand\'s biggest radio station. \r\n\r\nI was wondering if you might be available for a short interview about Brexit? \r\n\r\nWe would love to hear your opinion and analysis on this, and it would be fabulous if you had the time to spare. \r\n\r\nThe interview would be around 3 minutes long, for example at 6 pm either tomorrow, or on Thursday UK time. We are quite flexible with regards to the time, so do let me know if a different time suits better for you. \r\n\r\nI look forward to hearing from you, it would be fantastic if this would be a possibility for you. \r\n\r\nBest wishes,\r\nLaura Kneer'),(3051,'Hi Stanley,\r\nI hope you are well. I know your colleague Patrick Foulis, when he lived in Mumbai. In fact he spoke at a conference I put together a couple of years ago. I just wanted to reach out to introduce myself and hopefully catch up over a coffee to discuss education companies in India. I hope to hear back from you soon. \r\nBest, \r\nNitya Khemlani'),(3059,'The host of our radio talk program, Mark Sutcliffe, is interested in speaking with someone who would be able to talk generally about the \"Brexit\" vote, the history of how it got to this point, and the implications of the results, either way. The segments run about 8-11 minutes long and we\'re looking to have someone on the program on Thursday June 23 at 9:15am(EDT) .'),(3074,'Writing to ask Zanny to please do an interview with Hardball this evening, prepping at 5pm Eastern, with Joy Reid hosting from 30 Rock. Can do from DC, London, or wherever.\r\n\r\nPlease let me know asap.\r\n\r\nThank you\r\n\r\nCarol Joynt\r\nProducer\r\nHardball with Chris Matthews'),(3089,'Kaleel Ahamed.\r\nStudent at National School\r\nOf Business Management,\r\nSri Lanka.\r\n\r\n\r\nDear Sir/Madam.\r\nAsked to write an article\r\nI‘m K. Ahamed .I’m studying at NSBM University Sri Lanka and we have to prepare financial magazine regard any country’s present economic and financial situation. According to our assignment we have to choose one country in the world and have to interview (take an article) with subject experts. We chose your country (Russia) as our topic country.  We need an article from you and I would like to have an article from you. After that we have to put it into our magazine (Assignment report). I hope you will help us to do this very success and gain more marks for us. We have only four more days. Please sent it if you can with in these time period. (The assignment description give word limit for article is about 1000 to 1500. Please help us to score well marks.)\r\nThank you!\r\nYou’re faithful\r\nK. Ahamed'),(3097,'I am a former BBC foreign correspondent and Economist subscriber. I don\'t do Twitter but my husband forwarded your tweet about what happened in your neighbourhood. In mine - Islington - I went to the co-op on the Calendonian Road tonight and there was a group of 15 ish white boys shouting abuse at an Asian man at a chicken shop telling him their parents had voted for him to leave and he was going now. He was on his own and there were 15 of them. It was horrible. I told them I was calling the police so they threatened me as well. I left for my own safety and called the police who said they would come. I covered the Rwandan genoise and was given an MBE for it and then 9/11. I\'ve seen enough hate.'),(3104,'Dear Ananyo,\r\n\r\nI’d like to invite you (or a member of your team if you are unavailable) to join us to celebrate the publication of Tom Bulford’s debut book, The Future of Investing: How Biotechnology Could Transform Your Portfolio.\r\n\r\nWe’ll be hosting a small get-together at Jamies Fleet Place on Wednesday 29th June 2016 in the city of London.\r\n\r\n(Full address: 1 Fleet Place, Holborn Viaduct London  EC4M 7RA)\r\n\r\nThere’ll be beer, wine and a free copy of the book itself – so make sure you arrive on time. We’ll be kicking off at 7pm.\r\n\r\nAs well as Tom, you’ll also have the opportunity to talk with many of our editors, including Daily Reckoning editor, Ben Traynor, Penny Share Letter editor, Sean Keyes and Strategic Intelligence investment director, David Stevenson.\r\n\r\nIt promises to be a stimulating evening and I hope you’ll be able to join us.\r\n\r\nIf you’re able to attend please RSVP by emailing me on gorafinancialuk@agorapub.co.uk\r\n\r\nRegards\r\n\r\nDarren Hughes\r\nManaging Director\r\nAgora Financial UK Ltd\r\n\r\n\r\nAdvance praise for The Future of Investing: How Biotechnology Could Transform Your Portfolio...\r\n\r\n“Thoroughly enjoyed the book. You are the biotech Bill Bryson with an ability to explain the complex in easily understood terms.” – Richard Goodfellow, CEO, Scancell Holdings\r\n\r\n“Well written, accessible and a great companion guide to those who are new to the subject. I will be recommending we take a couple of copies for reference.” – Ian Lyall, Director, Proactive Investors\r\n\r\n“It’s full of very interesting facts but is very easy to understand. You have a rare talent for making complex science seem simple.” – Professor Lindy Durrant, The University of Nottingham\r\n\r\n“If you’re interested in not just understanding biotechnology but getting on the front foot and investing in it – and backing some of the most exciting and innovative companies in the world today – then The Future of Investing is a must read.” - Nick O’Connor, Associate Publisher, MoneyWeek\r\n\r\n“Easy to read and intriguing” - Richard Edwards, CEO, Anpario \r\n\r\n“I much enjoyed it. I think it carries off that difficult task of explaining what can be a complex and challenging sector to a generalist investor in an even handed and informative way.” - Steve Bates, CEO, BioIndustry Association'),(3111,'Dear Edward,\r\n\r\nI’d like to invite you (or a member of your team if you are unavailable) to join us to celebrate the publication of Tom Bulford’s debut book, The Future of Investing: How Biotechnology Could Transform Your Portfolio.\r\n\r\nWe’ll be hosting a small get-together at Jamies Fleet Place on