half of Snapdeal to share thier perspective on the same and share the latest developments within Snapdeal, including a shift in strategy\r\n\r\nLook forward to hearing from you.\r\n\r\nRegards,\r\nIshita'),(3175,'Dear Mr. Ostrovsky. I am doing a featue story on the controversies surrounding the film \"Magnitsky Act - Behind the scenes\" by Andrei Nekrasov, that Bill Browder has attempted to stop, and I would like to talk with you about this movie in the context of the information war between Russia and the West and the backdrop described in your excellent new book. Looking forward to your answer.'),(3183,'I m going to London next week, and would like, it she is available, to interview Ms Minton Beddoes on 6 July or 7 July. Ukeavisen Ledelse (\"the Weekly Leadership\") is a well known magazine in Norway cocerned wih, as the name implies, business leadershp. I would like to interview the editor-in-chef on the consequences for Britain of the referendum and on the choices that Britain is facing.'),(3191,'Hi my name is Rebecca and I just wanted to send you a quick note here instead of calling you. I came to your Tom Standage - Economist page and noticed you could have a lot more traffic. I have found that the key to running a successful website is making sure the visitors you are getting are interested in your website topic. There is a company that you can get keyword targeted visitors from and they let you try their service for free for 7 days. I managed to get over 300 targeted visitors to day to my site. http://goovernow.com/1v'),(3198,'To whom it may concern\r\n\r\nMadam, Sir,\r\n\r\nWe would be happy to welcome Mrs. Zanny Minton Beddoes as a moderator at the 9th Convergences World Forum which will be held in Paris from the 5th to the 7th of September, 2016.\r\n\r\nAs a unique space of meetings and mobilization, the Convergences World Forum gathers every year in Paris around 7000 participants of over 60 nationalities, representing both the public and private sectors, NGOs and associations, the academic world and the media, to face together the triple Zero challenge “Zero exclusion, Zero carbon, Zero poverty”, as well as the implementation of the Sustainable Development Goals.  This year’s edition will give prominence to the solutions contributing to a successful transition towards sustainable cities and territories around the globe.\r\n\r\nWe would be honoured if Mrs. Zanny Minton Beddoes could share with us her commitment to this global agenda for a fair and sustainable world. Her contribution to one of the high quality conferences as a moderator would greatly enriching the discussion. As the World Forum will take place from the 5th to the 7th September, would she be available on those dates?\r\n\r\nPlease do not hesitate to contact me should you need further information.\r\n\r\nThank you and I look forward to hearing from you.\r\n\r\nYours sincerely,\r\n\r\nAlix Bouillon'),(3206,'Hello, I\'d like to ask a couple questions The Economist got about the criticism from the article Helen Joyce commissioned about medicalizing FGM.\r\n\r\nI\'d like to understand the thinking behind this article. Do the authors believe that a gradual approach to making it safer for women that are subject to FGM because of cultural reasons is the best approach for now?\r\n\r\nOr do they believe that by medicalizing FGM, those that think it\'s essential to preserving their culture will actually go to the doctor?\r\n\r\nAlso, what about the psychological/emotional aspect of FGM...by medicalizing it, the risk of infection is gone, but there is still emotional trauma that follows the victims of FGM. \r\n\r\nWhy do you believe that there was so much backlash as well? I know you told the Guardian that it was your statement, but what was the statement The Economist was making? Was it one of pragmatism? Was your statement one of hope for the future?'),(3214,'Dear Ludwig\r\n\r\nI noticed an article on Slack in the Economist a few weeks back.... \r\n\r\nI represent MindLink who are in a similar space. We are due to send out a product announcement on 20th July - would you interested in speaking to them and seeing the release under embargo?\r\n\r\nMindLink is a Chat Enabled Collaboration (CEC) platform for global enterprises. Think of MindLink as a secure alternative to WhatsApp™ designed for corporate use. Its messaging and collaboration app which encourages employees to stay actively connected, reducing unnecessary email usage.  \r\n\r\nPlease let me know if this is of interest?\r\n\r\nKind Regards\r\nShamira Alidina\r\n+44 7801 590718'),(3222,'NHK World is the international English language channel of NHK / Japan Broadcasting Corporation, \r\npresenting the latest news and current affairs, as well as a wide variety of cultural programming. \r\nIt can be watched via satellite, cable TV, IPTV or through streaming on the NHK World website and app. NHK World can now be viewed in 150 countries around the globe. \r\n\r\n\"Global Agenda”, is a monthly program broadcast on NHK World and can be viewed across Europe, Asia and Americas.\r\nAnd our upcoming debate topic will be on Africa and its challenges towards sustainable and independent growth.\r\nhttp://www.nhk.or.jp/globalagenda/ \r\n\r\nThe upcoming panel discussion that will take place at Jomo Kenyatta University in Nairobi, Kenya on July 19th.  \r\n  \r\nWe are aware that 2016 is a crucial year for African countries as they seek to respond to shifting dynamics in the global economy\r\nand the urgent need for economic diversification for sustained inclusive growth. \r\nAs we face those challenges, we would like to hear opinions from experts on the below points:\r\n\r\n-  What are the obstacles and challenges that African nations are facing now?\r\n-  What was brought to Africa as a result of the international assistance from Western countries and China?\r\n-  What African nations and the international community can do to bring sustainable and self-reliance. What are your suggestions?    \r\n\r\nThe producers are very keen to have on board a speaker who would be able to discuss the above from a wider European / Western point of view. \r\nFurther details on the programme and the rundown of the debate can be sent by email. \r\n\r\nSince the recording is due to take place on the 19th July (in Nairobi) from 11am~ 12:30, it would be best if the panellist could fly in on the day before, \r\nand depending on flight times and availability, they may be able to fly back after the recording or on the following day. \r\nNHK will be able to pay for travel costs (taxis, flights, accommodation) and an honorarium if appropriate. (about 2000-3000 GBP).'),(3230,'I\'m working with one of the biggest tech companies in the world on a data-driven/storytelling project about the Syrian refugee crisis.  (Sorry, I\'ve signed an NDA and can\'t reveal which one quite yet but I\'m happy to discuss if we move forward).  We are very interested in your \"Refugee Relocation Index: Germany\" from April 25th, and we\'re wondering if you\'re planning on globalizing the index to include all relevant countries? And if you are currently not,  are there ways to partner with you to do so?  I\'d love to discuss further. Many thanks, Patti'),(3238,'I was just looking at your Tom Standage - Economist site and see that your site has the potential to become very popular. I just want to tell you, In case you don\'t already know... There is a website network which already has more than 16 million users, and most of the users are looking for topics like yours. By getting your website on this service you have a chance to get your site more popular than you can imagine. It is free to sign up and you can read more about it here: http://nt4.pl/u/2l - Now, let me ask you... Do you need your site to be successful to maintain your way of life? Do you need targeted traffic who are interested in the services and products you offer? Are looking for exposure, to increase sales, and to quickly develop awareness for your website? If your answer is YES, you can achieve these things only if you get your site on the service I am describing. This traffic service advertises you to thousands, while also giving you a chance to test the service before paying anything. All the popular blogs are using this service to boost their readership and ad revenue! Why aren’t you? And what is better than traffic? It’s recurring traffic! That\'s how running a successful site works... Here\'s to your success! Find out more here: http://ezurl.dk/gfc8'),(3254,'The piece I\'m writing is about the forthcoming elections; looking at the context, the likely outcomes and their impact. My deadline is Thursday so I would need to talk soon; hope Arkady can spare 15 minutes on the phone to talk.\r\n\r\nAll the best,\r\nAlec'),(3262,'Emma hits the nail on the head. One which farm journos like myself find very difficult to tackle. But farmers need to something other than the opinions of their powerful union. Re the farmers\' \'leave\' vote, both the farm minister Geo Eustice and the previous sec of state Owen Paterson are both strong leavers, and promised farmers the subsidies they have been getting, with Paterson saying the payments will be bigger. \r\nAs an independent magazine, not even with advertising, I\'d be interested in a short interview with  Emma ....  a good way to spell out reality without it being my views, which would result in mass cancellation of subscriptions!'),(3292,'FTO: Edward Carr\r\n\r\nMy name is Usman, I’m working for TRT World - that’s Turkey’s national broadcaster, its version of the BBC - which has recently launched an English language 24-hour news channel across the region and Europe, similar to France 24 or Al Jazeera.\r\n\r\nI’m working on its flagship current affairs programme which is made and broadcast from London. It’s an independent production called “Insight” and is hosted by Martin Stanford - the award-winning former Sky News anchor who led coverage of some of the biggest news stories of the past 25 years.\r\n\r\nThe aim of the show is to get to “the story behind the headlines”, to create space for informed discussion of current affairs issues - to provide analysis and context for the audience and to allow time for those debates to unfold.\r\n\r\nI was hoping Ed Carr was part of the pool of speakers that we get on the Friday press review show for the \'Insight\' show. His experience and expertise would really add value to the news commentary. I feel he would have something different to offer with perspectives on the headlines. \r\n \r\nIt is a 30 minute show. 2 slots of 13 minutes. Recoding will be at 2pm, but would want you in the studio by 1.20pm. \r\n \r\nIf you need more information, please do not hesitate to contact me. \r\n \r\nWe are based in Oxford Circus, London.'),(3308,'I would like to arrange an interview for this evening at 5.15pm GMT with Sophie Pedder. \r\n\r\nWe would like to talk about the political impact yesterdays attack will have. \r\n\r\nKind Regards\r\nDaniel Cahill'),(3316,'I am not a journalist, And I am in the process of applying to school. However, I have always read the Economist. Especially the Bagehot Column. I would like to know what he thinks, and conduct an interview as such.'),(3324,'I am not a journalist, And I am in the process of applying to school. However, I have always read the Economist. Especially the Bagehot Column. I would like to know what he thinks, and conduct an interview as such.'),(3332,'I am with To the Best of Our Knowledge, a Peabody award-winning radio program heard on over 220 NPR stations across the United States. \r\n\r\nWe are producing a show on light, and are interested in interviewing Ms. Wroe about her wonderful new book on the subject. The interview would last around 30-45 minutes and would be not be taped live. We would like to ensure the highest sound quality by interviewing her at her local BBC station. \r\n\r\nI really think Ms. Wroe would be a perfe