d back five times. What does this (seemingly astronomical) change mean for the future of the Indian economy? \r\n \r\nDemonetization is producing a contagion of fear across India. Merchants and street vendors are no longer accepting bills denominated in large amounts. The destitute who primarily transacted in paper, have essentially been rendered cashless. Even the ATM machines are running out of cash to exchange, while banks have imposed limits on the value of exchange. As a result of the monetary drought, Indians across all social classes are tying up capital by hoarding rupees of lesser value. Consequently, with limitations in trade and transaction, the economy is expected to contract as recession looms in the short-run, and fear permeates.\r\n \r\nThe real estate market is one particular market in which “under the table” transactions are customary, and home valuations are intentionally undervalued on paper to evade capital gains and stamp-duty taxes. In secondary market transactions, 60:40 serves as the normative ratio of legal to black money. The new wave of demonetization is expected to deter such illicit deals, decreasing the total number of transactions in the housing market, while increasing both the number of taxpayers, and, the amount of taxes paid. In this case, such a slump may persist well beyond the immediate horizon. Other industries hard hit by demonetization include wedding services, and luxury goods. \r\n \r\nAmidst slump in real-estate, Indian investors may shift to gold. If there is an increase in the aggregate demand for gold, foreign currency reserves will be depleted, as gold is an imported commodity. This could lead to restrictions on investment in gold. The recessionary effects of a slump may prolong in this instance. On the other hand, if Indians increase investments in productive sectors of the economy, like new ventures, the Indian economy will benefit.\r\n \r\nHowever, banks are not without recourse. Within an eight day span, Indian banks recapitalized a total of Rs. 5.44 lakh crores, or roughly $80 billion USD. This large injection into the Indian banking system will cause the rates to decline. Arundhati Bhattacharya, State Bank of India Chair announced, “All rates will fall… The bank has seen huge inflow of deposits but demand for credit has slowed down. Therefore, lending rates too will fall but after a gap.” Lower rates will stimulate investment. So, an expansionary effect is expected in the next year. \r\n \r\nMoreover, it is estimated that out of the 14 trillion rupees that have been purged from the system, three trillion rupees will not be exchanged or deposited at banks. Consequently, the RBI’s liabilities will reduce by three trillion rupees, i.e., the three trillion rupees will be void in the system, and the RBI will achieve an economic surplus of the same amount. This, in addition to the new inflow of taxes, will reduce the size of the budget deficit, and allow the Indian government to increase spending, welfare, and investment for greater development. Additionally, the attenuation in the monetary supply will decrease India’s inflation rate, which hovers above its optimal rate. Thus, expansion is expected in the long-run. \r\n \r\nIt is unclear to what extent Modi’s policy is effective in meeting its purported goals of eradicating “black money” as a necessary step to give Indians the India of their “dreams.” After all, “black money” is opaque and shifty, and the ban is disproportionately onerous on the ordinary Indian citizen. However, if the gears are all operating in the right positions, with time, they might just propel India forward.'),(4765,'Hi,\r\n\r\nI am conference producer of the Beyond Data event. We would like to enquire how to send an invitation to Kenneth Cukier to speak! The agenda can be found on http://www.smart-circle.org/beyonddata/ \r\n\r\nI look forward to hearing from you!\r\nLinda'),(4772,'The Ambassador of Japan to the EU, Mr Kazuo Kodama, would like to invite a s