n to the panel. Please let me know whether you\'d be open to chat about it over a call or email\r\n\r\nBest,\r\nSimon Hudson\r\n514-553-5506\r\n\r\nFor a little more information, here are some links about us, Element AI, and the conference:\r\n\r\nThe AI Forum is a part of C2Montreal.\r\n\r\nElement AI:\r\nhttps://www.wired.com/2016/10/ai-pioneer-yoshua-bengio-launching-element-ai-deep-learning-incubator/\r\n\r\nhttp://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/microsoft-investment-in-element-ai-bolsters-montreals-status-as-ai-hub/article33294325/'),(7521,'Hi,\r\n\r\nI met Tom Standage at the last AOP event and we agreed that it would be great if The Economist could guest-appear on Grazia\'s Facebook live events to discuss current affairs. Will be great if we can make it work? Our plans is to get readers to submit their questions and we answer them live. It\'s a great opportunity for the economist to meet new subscriber base in the UK.\r\n\r\nBest,\r\nCathy\r\n\r\nAudience and Content Director,\r\nBauer Media'),(7537,'TO FIAMMETTA ROCCO FROM BELEN PALANCO\r\n\r\nDear Fiametta, \r\nThis is Belén Palanco, art writer and contributor for dailies and magazines of Spain and United Kingdom (The Art Newspaper).\r\nIn this case, I am working on a commission for Spanish daily El Español on the art market and UK museums after the Brexit. I would like to know your opinion on museums and write some quotes. Would it be able to arrange a short interview (just 2-3 questions)? \r\nThanks in advance for your reply.\r\n \r\nBest regards, \r\nBelén Palanco \r\n\r\nbelpal@gmail.com'),(7553,'Please see my website at https://eco-kare.com/news/\r\nI recently read The Economist recent article \'Bird brains and traffic accidents\' and thought that I could write an article on the topic of \'turtles and traffic accidents\' Turtles are killed on the road because the females nest on road shoulders and because they often move long distances to find suitable egg-laying grounds. As a solution we install turtle exclusionary fencing and animal underpass tunnels along roads that bisect wetlands. We have pictures of turtles going through three larger tunnels. See https://eco-kare.com/wildlife-monitoring/wildlife-monitoring-highway-69-reptile-tunnels/\r\nThank-you, Kari'),(7569,'Dear Sophie,\r\n\r\nI\'m a producer for the Colin McEnroe Show on public radio WNPR in the United States. \r\n\r\nI\'m hoping you can join us Monday, April 24, 1:00 pm-1:25 pm Eastern - which would be 7:00 pm in France - to talk about the French elections. \r\n\r\nThis election has captured the attention of the world. What is different this time? What is at stake? What\'s next?\r\n\r\nI realize the time change makes it late for you to join us. If you\'re interested, we can pretape with you earlier in your day. \r\n\r\nThank you,\r\nBetsy Kaplan\r\n\r\n***\r\nSenior producer, Colin McEnroe Show\r\nWNPR'),(7592,'In March 2014 Belgium’s King Philippe signed into law a controversial bill that allowed chronically ill children to be euthanized. In opposition to the signing of this law I wrote an editorial to many Christian and Catholic magazines throughout Western Europe that requested their support in lobbying against the King\'s signing of this. Unfortunately, the king signed the bill into law.  According to RT News, \"The legislation granted children (in Belgium) the right to request euthanasia if they are “in great pain” and there is no available treatment, makes Belgium the first country in the world where the age of the child is not taken into consideration. Similar legislation exists in the Netherlands, though only for children over the age of 12, and in both countries, children are required to receive the consent of parents, doctors and psychiatrists.\" Belgium’s law, which is known to be the most liberal in the world, extends euthanasia to being available to anyone who is in “constant and unbearable physical or mental suffering that cannot be alleviated.”\r\n \r\nEuthanasia, is “the act or practice of killing someone who is very sick or injured in order to prevent any more suffering.\"  Both the Netherlands and Belgium allow euthanasia to be carried out in non-terminal illnesses and for psychological conditions such as depression.\r\n \r\nAs of April 2016 a total of 12,762 people had been euthanized in Belgium, with 2,022 people in 2015 alone - a record number of people in one year. In the space of a decade, instances of people choosing to end their lives this way rose nearly eight-fold - 800 percent - from 235 to 1,807 cases, especially amongst those who were not terminally ill.  \r\n \r\nIn September of 2016, the first child was publicly reported to have been euthanized in Belgium.  With Belgium\'s law no age limit is set, but the children who are euthanized have “to possess the capacity of discernment.” However, does a child - terminally ill or not - have the capacity to discern if they should die? \r\n \r\nIn pursuing certification as a Child Life Specialist, one who reduces the trauma of the hospital experience for children with the promotion of coping strategies and play techniques, I undertook a review of all literature on the topic of a healthy child\'s understanding of the concept of death based on medical and psychological research published on the topic. In my paper, \"A Child\'s Understanding of the Concept of Death\", I found that a child does not cognitively grasp what death is or means until 11 years of age, and in the field of child development it is known that at this age of a child\'s physical and emotional development, the healthy child has not yet developed the decision-making skills to effectively guide their own life so is dependent upon a parent to continue rearing them. \r\n \r\nJean Piaget, one of the world\'s leading pioneers in the field of child development, is a psychologist who has also identified cognitive-developmental stages of the perspective of death. He concludes that full comprehension of death and dying does not occur until all subcomponents are understood, and these subcomponents are: Irreversibility (the dead cannot come back to life); Universality (all living things and only living things die); Personal mortality (death applies to oneself); Inevitability (all living things must die eventually); Cessation (bodily and mental functions cease after death); Causality (death is ultimately caused by a breakdown of bodily functions); and Unpredictability (the timing of (natural) death is not known in advance). For a healthy child who is cognitively developing learns in proportion to their stage of development, these subcomponents are understood by the child as follows:\r\no       temporary, reversible, concrete -the first stage (Preoperational). This can be understood by children 2 - 7 years of age and death is perceived by them as being still and having closed eyes, but waking up sometime in the future.\r\no       caused by concrete elements from outside of the body and not seen as part of the intrinsic and natural part of the life cycle, although all living things must die and death is irreversible. This is the second stage (Concrete Operational) and can be understood by children 7 - 11 years of age where the child sees death as something happens to someone else, typically a grandparent or older person, by something outside of the body, but not within their own bodies.\r\no       inevitable, universal, the last stage in the life cycle of all living organisms, which includes cessation of all bodily functions and is consistent with the adult perspective of death. This is the final stage (Formal Operational) and can be understood by children 11 years and older. This child can understand what death means, but would not have developed the decision-making skills to guide their own life. As a result, an adult or parents are required to continue raising the child and guiding the decisions that inform their life and development.\r\n \r\nAs a result, in allowing a child to request to die, if parents and psychologist or doctors affirm this request, then the parents and pscychologist/doctors are guilty of murder because the request by a healthy and normal child cannot be cognitively understood by this child in its totality to warrant \"informed consent\"- let alone by a terminally or chronically ill child, whose development is typically delayed due to a retraction from normal activities and interactions that influence cognitive development, as well as physical brain development.\r\n \r\nI call upon the Christian Democratic Flemish Society to do what they can to bring this matter to the European Court of Human Rights if it is not too late, and call upon the church and The Economist to expose the egregiousness of this law to the Belgian and European influencers who can effectively change this law in support of the next generation of Belgian\'s society. I hope you will cover the absurdity of this law. It is our duty to protect today\'s children and in allowing a child to request to end their own life when they do not have an understanding of what this means is in no way upholding our responsibility as adults in the society we live.\r\n \r\nI have sent this email and a copy of my paper \"A Child\'s Understanding of the Concept of Death\" for a deeper understanding to Hollydonahue@economist.com. Please contact her or me to obtain a copy.\r\n \r\nSources:\r\n \r\nChildren\'s Euthanasia Bill Signed by Belgium King\r\nhttps://www.rt.com/news/belgium-king-sign-euthanasia-bill-566/\r\n \r\nEuthanasia Deaths Hit Record High in Belgium. Why That Matters to the US.\r\nhttp://dailysignal.com/2016/11/03/euthanasia-deaths-hit-record-high-in-belgium-why-that-matters-for-the-us/  \r\n \r\n800% increase: Euthanasia spikes in Belgium, especially among non-terminally ill\r\nhttps://www.rt.com/news/359542-euthanasia-rise-belgium-study/\r\n \r\nFirst Child Dies After Belgium Approves Measure to Euthanize Children\r\nhttp://www.lifenews.com/2016/09/19/first-child-dies-a